4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, public K-12 schools are
6 annually assigned a grade based on school and district
7 performance.
8 This bill would exclude from consideration all
9 accountability metrics for students on alternative
10 education pathways who receive a non-standard high
11 school diploma upon graduation, instead of the standard
12 Alabama High School Diploma, when assigning grades to a
13 school or school district on its annual report card.
14
15
16 A BILL
17 TO BE ENTITLED
18 AN ACT
19
20 Relating to public K-12 education and the school report
21 card; to amend Section 16-6C-2, Code of Alabama 1975, to
22 exclude from consideration all accountability metrics of
23 students who are on alternative education pathways and receive
24 a non-standard high school diploma upon graduation instead of
25 an Alabama High School Diploma when assigning the annual grade
26 to a school or school district on their annual report card.
27 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
28 Section 1. Section 16-6C-2 of the Code of Alabama 1975,
Page 1

Section 1. Section 16-6C-2 of the Code of Alabama 1975,
HB406 INTRODUCED
29 is amended to read as follows:
30 "§16-6C-2
31 (a) In addition to any other labels or designations
32 assigned to public schools and public school districts
33 pursuant to a federal, state, school, district, or other
34 assessment or accountability system, the State Superintendent
35 of Education, consistent with this chapter, shall develop a
36 school grading system reflective of school and district
37 performance. The grading system shall utilize the traditional
38 A, B, C, D, or F framework.
39 (1) Schools receiving a grade of "A" are making
40 excellent progress.
41 (2) Schools receiving a grade of "B" are making above
42 average progress.
43 (3) Schools receiving a grade of "C" are making
44 satisfactory progress.
45 (4) Schools receiving a grade of "D" are making less
46 than satisfactory progress.
47 (5) Schools receiving a grade of "F" are failing to
48 make adequate progress.
49 (b) In developing this school grading system, the State
50 Superintendent of Education shall seek input from parents,
51 teachers, school administrators, existing State Department of
52 Education advisory groups or task forces, and other education
53 stakeholders on how the system can properly reflect not only
54 the overall academic proficiency of each public school but
55 also the academic improvements made by each public school,
56 along with other key performance indicators that give a total
Page 2

along with other key performance indicators that give a total
HB406 INTRODUCED
57 profile of the school or the school system, or both.
58 (c) The State Superintendent of Education shall
59 prescribe the design and content of the school grading system
60 by not later than December 31, 2012. It is the intent of the
61 Legislature that the system be in place by no later than the
62 2013-2014 school year. The system may not be utilized by the
63 State Superintendent of Education or the State Department of
64 Education until sufficient rules have been adopted by the
65 State Board of Education pursuant to the Alabama
66 Administrative Procedure Act.
67 (d) Using an easy to understand grading scale, the
68 school grading system shall describe achievement in the state,
69 each district, and each school. Additionally, the State
70 Superintendent of Education shall not be precluded from also
71 assigning grades to school feeder patterns or grades that
72 reflect the fiscal health and fiscal efficiency of a school or
73 school system.
74 (e) The State Superintendent of Education shall make
75 these grades available to the general public and shall post
76 these grades on the website of the State Department of
77 Education as soon as the grades are available. Additionally,
78 appropriate grade information shall be delivered to the parent
79 or guardian of each public school student at least once
80 annually in the same manner that student report cards are
81 currently delivered.
82 (f)(1) Using state-authorized assessments and other key
83 performance indicators that give a total profile of the school
84 or the school system, or both, a school's grade, at a minimum,
Page 3

or the school system, or both, a school's grade, at a minimum,
