85 shall be based on a combination of student achievement scores,
86 achievement gap, college and career readiness, learning gains,
87 and other indicators as determined by the State Superintendent
88 of Education to impact student learning and success.
89 (2)a. Commencing with the 2021-2022 school year, the
90 academic achievement of each student identified as an English
91 language learner who has not shown proficiency on ACCESS for
92 EL, or other state-approved English proficiency assessment,
93 may not be considered in assigning an academic achievement
94 grade to a school or school system for the first five years of
95 enrollment of the student. The educational progress of each of
96 these students shall continue to be measured in the academic
97 growth category and the progress in English language
98 proficiency category, and, at the end of the five-year period
99 for the student, his or her proficiency shall again be
100 considered in assigning an academic achievement grade to a
101 school or school system on the state A-F school grading
102 system.
103 b. Commencing with the 2024-2025 school year, the
104 academic achievement of each student identified as a transfer
105 student from a nonpublic school may not be considered in
106 assigning an academic achievement grade to a school or school
107 system for the first three years of enrollment of the transfer
108 student. The educational progress of each of these transfer
109 students shall continue to be measured in the academic growth
110 category, and, beginning with the fourth year of enrollment of
111 the transfer student, his or her academic achievement shall be
112 considered in assigning an academic achievement grade to a
Page 4

considered in assigning an academic achievement grade to a
HB406 INTRODUCED
113 school or school system on the state A-F school grading
114 system.
115 c. Commencing with the 2026-2027 school year, the
116 accountability metrics of each student who is on an
117 alternative education pathway and is destined to receive a
118 non-standard diploma upon graduation, instead of the Alabama
119 High School Diploma, may not be considered in assigning grades
120 for any accountability metrics to a school or school system on
121 their annual report card during his or her enrollment.
122 (3) The State Superintendent of Education may not amend
123 the state Every Student Succeeds Act option for including test
124 scores of English language learners enrolled in United States
125 schools. The option provides as follows: For the first year of
126 enrollment, the test scores shall be reported, but the results
127 on both the reading/language arts and math tests shall be
128 excluded from the federal accountability system; for the
129 second year of enrollment, a measure of student growth on both
130 tests shall be included in the federal accountability system;
131 and for the third year of enrollment, proficiency on both
132 tests shall be included in the federal accountability system.
133 Additionally, the option requires English language learners
134 who have successfully left the English language learner
135 subgroup by attaining English proficiency to be included in
136 that subgroup for accountability purposes for four years.
137 (g) The A-F school grading system shall be consistently
138 applied so that grades of one school or system may be compared
139 to the grades of any other school or system."
